  "body":"Currently, some Roam users download the browser extension [roam-toolkit](https://github.com/roam-unofficial/roam-toolkit) to get additional features such as custom CSS overrides and additional keybindings.\r\n\r\nGiven that Roam is a text editor, it makes more sense to me that customizations be a native experience. Can we take inspiration from Atom and VS Code to see what a modern plugin architecture looks like? This architecture ideally supports a variety of use cases:\r\n\r\n- custom themes\r\n- custom keybindings (e.g. Vim, Emacs)\r\n- arbitrarily executable and composable code\r\n\r\nSome Inspirations\r\n- [VS Code Extension API](https://code.visualstudio.com/api)\r\n- [org-mode](https://orgmode.org/features.html)\r\n  - scheduling and planning your GTD agenda\r\n  - tracking time\r\n  - native capture templates (as opposed to text expanders)\r\n  - export (to HTML, PDF, LaTex, slideshow)\r\n  - literate programming\r\n- Smallest Federated Wiki\r\n  - [data viz with d3.js](http://video.fed.wiki.org/view/welcome-visitors/view/federated-wiki-videos/view/07-data-d3-binding). With sci.web, we can import arbitrary `npm` packages on the client. A use case for this would be importing data visualization libraries and having ObservableHQ workflows inside your Athens. See #67.\r\n  - [arduino sensor data](http://video.fed.wiki.org/view/welcome-visitors/view/federated-wiki-videos/view/04-arduino-sensor-data-wiki). Imagine ingesting actionable live data from IFTTT or Zapier into your Athens.",
